| But what is different between calling `Rf_error` within the `catch`
| block, and calling `Rf_error` in a separate `if` block (and
| constructing a new exception on the spot, rather than forwarding the
| previous one by reference)? Shouldn't destructors already have had a
| chance to run after the exception is thrown? (Not necessarily
| expecting you to know, but hopefully someone else on the list does...)

"It is complicated".  

Around the time of Rcpp 0.8.* / 0.9.* (ie before Rcpp Attributes) an R Core
member (who is rather familiar with the very internals of R) questioned our
use of exception for the very reason that it may get in the way of R longjmp
statements.

On balance, I still believe this does the Right Thing (TM) in most cases and
for most people: it gives a pretty robust and elegant way to catch errors in
many situations, and frees people from having to do this themselves.

Nobody is forced to use this. Rcpp Attributes are not mandatory, and folks
can use .Call() directly without our try/catch wrapper. We don't hide
anything either.

So if Wush does indeed have a better way, we'd be happy to see it but as you
say we would also be careful to compare apples to apples.
 
